Page 1 – Introduction
🔹 Git vs GitHub
Git → Tool that runs on your computer
GitHub → Platform that runs on the internet
🔹 Simple Understanding
Git = Engine
GitHub = Cloud storage + collaboration platform
🔹 What is Git?

Git is:

Installed on your local system
Tracks your code changes
Works offline
Manages versions of code

👉 You can use Git without GitHub

📄 Page 2 – GitHub & Workflow
🔹 What is GitHub?

GitHub is:

A cloud platform
Stores Git repositories online
Helps teams collaborate
Provides features like:
Pull Requests (PRs)
Issues
CI/CD

👉 GitHub internally uses Git

🔹 Real-World Analogy
Git → Your local notebook
GitHub → Google Drive
🔹 How They Work Together

Flow (from page diagram):

Your Laptop (Git)  ⇄  GitHub (Cloud)
🔹 Step-by-Step Workflow
You write code (local system)
Git tracks changes
You commit changes
You push to GitHub
📄 Page 3 – Commands & Final Understanding
🔹 Key Points
GitHub is useless without Git
Git is powerful even without GitHub
🔹 Example Workflow
Step 1 – Initialize Project
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"

👉 Everything is stored locally

🔹 Connect to GitHub
git remote add origin <repo-url>
git push -u origin main

👉 Now your project is online

🔹 Final Definition

Git is a distributed version control system used to track changes locally, while GitHub is a cloud-based platform used to host repositories and enable collaboration.

🚀 Summary
Git → Version control (local)
GitHub → Hosting + collaboration (cloud)
Together → Complete development workflow